Spotify Song Analysis¶

A question the music industry has been pondering for decades is how possible it is to predict a songs popularity. Popularity means increased sales figures after all, so this question is of great significane. We intrinsically know that a popular song has to be catchy, memorable, and has a good beat. But how can we quantify this? Can we prove or derive a formula to predict popularity based on several various attributes?

In this tutorial, I'd like to examine if there are any similarities between popular songs. What overlaps are there? Happy, uplifting songs? Some other combination of variables?

Good thing theres an API to examine exactly this.

The Spotify API allows song data to be accessed and analyzed. There are 13 variables we will consider in this tutorial:

  • popularity *
  • duration_ms
  • danceability
    • "Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable."
  • energy
    • "Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale. Perceptual features contributing to this attribute include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy."
  • key
    • "The key the track is in. Integers map to pitches using standard Pitch Class notation. E.g. 0 = C, 1 = C/D, 2 = D, and so on. If no key was detected, the value is -1."
  • loudness
    • in decibels (dB). typically range between -60 and 0 db.
  • mode
    • modality (major or minor) of a track, the type of scale from which its melodic content is derived. Major is represented by 1 and minor is 0."
  • speechiness
    • "The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. Values above 0.66 describe tracks that are probably made entirely of spoken words. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 describe tracks that may contain both music and speech, either in sections or layered, including such cases as rap music. Values below 0.33 most likely represent music and other non-speech-like tracks."
  • acousticness
    • "A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. 1.0 represents high confidence the track is acoustic."
  • instrumentalness
    • "Predicts whether a track contains no vocals. "Ooh" and "aah" sounds are treated as instrumental in this context. Rap or spoken word tracks are clearly "vocal". The closer the instrumentalness value is to 1.0, the greater likelihood the track contains no vocal content. Values above 0.5 are intended to represent instrumental tracks, but confidence is higher as the value approaches 1.0."
  • liveness
    • "Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live. A value above 0.8 provides strong likelihood that the track is live."
  • valence
    • "A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry)."
  • tempo
    • "The overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM). In musical terminology, tempo is the speed or pace of a given piece and derives directly from the average beat duration."

A full reference to these variables can be found here (https://developer.spotify.com/documentation/web-api/reference/#/operations/get-several-audio-features).

Given a combination of these variables, could any given song be predicted to be popular or not? If so, could songs be created with these variables in mind?

Data Collection, Cleaning, and Management¶

In this section we will download song data from select Spotify playlists and use it to construct a .csv file.

The selected playlists are the following: (ideally first 100 songs of each)

  • "Greatest 90s Music Hits - Best Songs of 1990 to 2000" by redmusiccompany
    • https://open.spotify.com/playlist/0y0ZEQHqEdMPnQKqRKhSmn
  • "2000s-2010s bangers" by gians85
    • https://open.spotify.com/playlist/15sZyUgStYmvzm3QfdVDIp
  • "BEST SONGS 2010-2021" by BEST SONGS
    • https://open.spotify.com/playlist/1PIhV6X7PV4TjAQb7unitN

These playlists were selected arbitrarily. I desired to get some sample of songs spanning a decent period of time; the inclusion of 1990s to 2021 songs fulfils this concern. Ideally I'd want to limit bias from my datasets whenever possible. If not possible, then keeping this in mind is paramount in analysing data properly.

Since data is being pulled from 3 separate sources, ensure there are no duplicates in the final dataframe. The analysis that follows will work with the first 100 songs of these 3 playlists.

We save this data into a csv for sake of backup. Just in case Spotify API crashes or some connection issue occurs, this csv ensures our data is never gone forever.

In [117]:
# This is the column array for the final result of this section, a clean dataframe backed up by a csv export
track_columns = ['id', 'name', 'artist', 'popularity', 'duration_ms', 'danceability', 'energy', 'key', 'loudness', 'mode', 'speechiness', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence', 'tempo']


# this function adds the 'playlist_link' playlist's songs into the 'playlist_df' dataframe
#   ensures no repeat songs (checks by ID)
#   playlist_link: string of spotify url

def obtain_clean_playlist(playlist_df, playlist_link):
    
    playlist_URI = playlist_link.split("/")[-1].split("?")[0]
    playlist = sp.playlist(playlist_URI)
    
    print('Playlist Name: ' + str(playlist['name']))
    print('Playlist Author: ' + str(playlist['owner']['display_name']))
    print()
    
    added = 0
    for track in playlist['tracks']['items']:
        aud = sp.audio_features(track['track']['id'])
        
        id = track['track']['id']
        
        if len(playlist_df[playlist_df.id == id]) == 0:
            
            to_add = list()

            to_add.append(id)
            to_add.append(track['track']['name'])
            to_add.append(track['track']['artists'][0]['name'])
            to_add.append(track['track']['popularity'])
            to_add.append(track['track']['duration_ms'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['danceability'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['energy'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['key'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['loudness'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['mode'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['speechiness'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['acousticness'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['instrumentalness'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['liveness'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['valence'])
            to_add.append(aud[0]['tempo'])

            playlist_df.loc[len(playlist_df.index)] = to_add
            added += 1
            
    print('\ttotal tracks added to dataframe: ' + str(added))
    print()
    
    return playlist_df


playlist_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = track_columns)

playlist_1990s = "https://open.spotify.com/playlist/0y0ZEQHqEdMPnQKqRKhSmn"
playlist_2000s = "https://open.spotify.com/playlist/15sZyUgStYmvzm3QfdVDIp"
playlist_2010s = "https://open.spotify.com/playlist/1PIhV6X7PV4TjAQb7unitN"

playlist_df = obtain_clean_playlist(playlist_df, playlist_1990s)
playlist_df = obtain_clean_playlist(playlist_df, playlist_2000s)
playlist_df = obtain_clean_playlist(playlist_df, playlist_2010s)

playlist_df.to_csv('track_data.csv')

print('finished')

There appears to be a two signifcant clusters in this dataset: popularity close to 0 and popularity between 60 and 80. Visually, it seems that the dataset trends towards moderate tempo/valence, little lower in liveness, low in acousticness and speechiness, very low in instrumentalness, and higher in loudness and energy. Its very interesting that several all hold roughly similar patterns. The scatters are of course different in signficant ways but nonetheless theres patterns between variables. This will be discussed further later in this tutorial. Additionally, it seems that this dataset is skewed towards songs below 5 minutes (majority clustered below 300000 for duration_ms). I would suspect that this skew was due to the music industry and their production standards. There is a precedent in the music industry that songs must be of certain length. Historic reasons most likely caused this trend. Now lets look at the distribution of popularity values.

These are very unique graphs compared to the others. These graphs have significant clustering close to the origin sprawling out. Might there be a concentration of low acousticness, speechiness, and/or liveness songs in this dataset?

In summary, several hypotheses can be theorized from these graphs:

  • are acousticness, speechiness, and liveness are related?
  • are energy v loudness are positively correlated?
  • are energy v acousticness are negatively correlated?
  • are songs with popularity rating between 60 and 90 have liveness, acousticness, and speechiness pretty low, around 0.1. This is at or below the mean with these metrics.

In the next several sections, we will test these hypotheses.

Communication of Insights attained¶

In the dataset, if popularity is 60 to 90 then theres a good chance liveness/acousticness/speechiness value decreases slightly compared to the average.

Even though their graphs look very similar, acousticness, speechiness, and liveness are not correlated.

Acousticness, loudness, and valence can be used to predict energy rating for 62.203% of the data (according to the coefficient of determination). This is the best predictive model obtained from this tutorial. We obtained this by rank ordering energy correlation with other column variables and selecting the most correlative one after another to include as a input variable. This resulted in a functional model that is a rough estimater but accurate.
